post_text:
Granite State Arts Academy is so excited to be opening for in-person learning this fall with a remote option for students and families who need to continue learning at home.

We have missed our students and we can’t wait to see you all on September 8th for freshman and September 9th for all grade levels.

Our school may look a little different with even smaller classes and new desks but we are still the same exclusive arts integrated charter school you have come to know and love!

Learn more about our school: www.gsaanh.org

The graduating class of 2020
We had a graduating class of 26 in our 6th year as a school and 19 of them are off to college in the fall.

Below is a list of colleges the class of 2020 are attending and their fields of study: Bachelor of Arts in Computer Engineering and a Bachelor of Engineering, Game and Art Design, Nursing, Theatre & Performance, Dance, Art and Psychology, Business, Education, Missionary, Holistic Psychology & Wellness, Creative Writing, Animation and Game Art, Music Therapy, Psychology (concentration in Mental Health)

post_text: Happy Teacher 👩‍🏫 👨‍🏫 appreciation week from the students at GSAA.
text: Happy Teacher 👩‍🏫 👨‍🏫 appreciation week from the students at GSAA.

post_text:
An unexpected opportunity for our Theatre students!

Some of you may not know that our Theatre teacher Mrs. Lyons is a volunteer at a local rabbit rescue, House Rabbit Network. She is a foster home as well as an adoption counselor at her local shelter.

In all the theatre classes, we compiled the names of male characters in all the scripts that we have read this semester (minus the villains and creepy characters.) Our goal was to give him a name that will help him be adopted faster and so would have some social media appeal as well. We also considered input from his foster family on his personality. A poll was created and the voting results are in!

Everyone, meet "Baby Boy-C" who is now named Herbie!
Herbie is a very lovable and loyal character from the musical, Gypsy.

I think this name will appeal to potential adopters and help this guy find a loving home!

Way to go GSAA students! We're rooting for you, Herbie!

Our sewing teacher Mrs. Paula Trout has officially sewn and donated over 820 masks in the last month on her own to front line and essential workers. 80 of these in the last week have gone to the Salem Fire Department!

As a teacher and a person she exudes our mission of life long learning and community service. GSAA is truly blessed to have her as a part of our family!

When you add the masks made by students and faculty we are nearing 1,000 masks since this started!

Thank you!

post_text:
Mrs. Trout has been a blessing to our school and her and her sewing department are being blessings to our community!

To date, a total of 443 masks have been sewn and donated to various facilities in need. Most recently, 105 masks went to the Salem School District Bus Drivers and Paras that are delivering breakfasts and lunches throughout the town of Salem to any children under the age of 18.

Anyone who wishes to participate can contact me at p.trout@gsaanh.com and I can schedule pick up and distribution of masks as they are created.

If you have a specific facility that is in need, also let me know and I can add them to the list of facilities to donate to.

post_text:
The cast of the national tour of My Fair Lady joined the American Musical and Historical Theatre classes this past Wednesday on Zoom. After introducing themselves, the actors and actresses performed short scenes and explained the process of learning the multiple English dialects used in the show. Our students were treated to Scottish, British, and Cockney accent demonstrations. To top off the class, the students participated in a Q&A with the cast who gave advice to our young actors and told us what life on tour is like! It was a memorable and exciting experience for all of us!

#NHLearnsRemotely #schoolchoice #NHCharterschools

March 31 at 1:23 PM ·

Our first remote learning art project.

Consider the current situation we are in with the closing of schools and quarantine happening around us. Think about the feelings of panic, fear, confusion and anxiety that people are experiencing now. How do you feel personally about all of this? Think about those feelings and imagine what they might look like if you put a tangible form to them. Is it a familiar object? Is it a particular color? Write down some descriptive words regarding what it looks like and create a piece of art that represents how you feel.

#NHLearnsRemotely

post_text:
Be aware that GSAA will remain closed for all students until Monday, March 30. No activities of any kind will take place within the building. A more detailed letter will be sent out to all members of the GSAA community within the next 24 hours. We will let you know via this alert system when that letter is sent out.

Also, at this time the school will be unavailable For entry to any member of the GSAA community. However, we will let you know when you can come pick up your personal belongings. We will keep you updated as we become updated by the New Hampshire Department of education and Governor Sununu.

At this time the school is not staffed and will be unavailable to answer any questions but we are making a plan for that now.

All faculty and staff must report to GSAA at 8 AM on Tuesday, March 17.

Our 6th Annual Gala was a roaring good time!
Thank you to everyone who came out in support of our school and students we look forward to seeing you all at next year‘s Gala.

Some of our guests were unable to attend and asked if they could make a donation after the Gala was over so we made a giving link: www.gsaanh.org/gala

However we did fall short of our fundraising needs by $8,811.00. Many of you who could not attend or were concerned about attending have asked for a way to donate online.

Our best fundraiser of the night and one you can still help greatly with is our Fund A Future effort. This is a direct donation to fill the gap between the $14,500.00 traditional schools get per student and the $7,188.00 Charters get per student. This money goes to direct support of students and curriculum.

Please help us reach our goal !!!
Only $8,811.00 more to raise. We can do it. And you can help.

post_text:
Congratulations to GSAA’s Robotics club on receiving the:
Collins Aerospace Innovate Award:
This unique rookie team has shown us that form and function are important elements in a robot design. It all started with an inspired teacher who challenged his students, with no FIRST experience, to 'act' in a different role. Their basic robot design featured a harvester mechanism which ''artfully'' captured the stone. The Innovate Award goes to: Team 17455, the Granite State Arts Academy Octofighters!

The GSAA Robotics Club had a very successful first Qualifier at Alvirne High School. After winning the Judge’s Award, as well as being nominated for several other awards (including an award for the most creative design), they qualified for the state championship!

The GSAA Octofighters will be at the SKYSTONE championship at SNHU on February 16th. You can also check them out at their second Qualifier at Merrimack High on February 2nd.

post_text:
With our 6th Annual Gala coming up on March, 13th we are celebrating 100 years since the Roaring '20s!

We are seeking corporate sponsors and we are offering a tiered level for sponsorships, including tickets for a table, ads in our program and more. Please call or email Renia at r.friend@gsaanh.com for more info. Early bird sponsors will get on our invitations but you must submit your sponsorship paperwork by January 20th. After the 20th sponsors will be put on all of our programs, website, and advertisements for the event in print and social media. Every sponsor will also be posted on posters in various locations during the event (entryway, buffets, tables, and bars)

We are also looking for corporate or business donations for our Silent Auction Table. If you own a business or work for a company that may be interested in donating a tax-deductible item please call or email Deb Richards at deb.richards@gsaanh.com.

If you would like to volunteer by helping us collect items for auction and/or sponsorships please email Deb Richards.

post_text:
Today Is Giving Tuesday So Start Sharing
If all of our followers would give just $10.00 that would be over $14,000 that could double with Facebook Giving match, here is a little more information about GSAA.

As a public charter school in NH, we are funded at about 45% of the funding that a traditional public school receives. Yet, with half the budget, we are expected to provide the same educational opportunities as a traditional high school. This reality means we must fill that funding gap through various forms of fundraising.

https://www.facebook.com/donate/1059919914339940/?fundraiser_source=external_url

GSAA is collecting New Unwrapped toys as part of the #karsonkennedy10Khighschoolchallenge from Mix 104.1! Mix 104.1 collects 10,000 toys for Girls and Boys to benefit Toys for Tots!

GSAA is a small school of 120 students and we have pledged a goal of 200 new unwrapped toys!

We are a small school in comparison to the other high schools of 1k + students and we are pledging twice our enrollment in toys where they are pledging half their enrollment in toys! Help us exceed this goal so we can help bring smiles and cheer to 10,000 girls and boys this Holiday season!
#ToysforTots
